description: From Medieval Latin invāgīnātus, past participle of Medieval Latin invāgīnāre, from in- + vāgīna (“sheath”).

entries.meaning: (biology) Having one portion of a hollow organ drawn back within another portion.

verbs.description: invaginate (third-person singular simple present invaginates, present participle invaginating, simple past and past participle invaginated)

entries.meaning: (medicine, surgery) To fold up or enclose into a sheath-like or pouch-like structure, either naturally or as part of a surgical procedure.
(medicine) To fold inward to create a hollow space where none had existed, as with a gastrula forming from a blastula.
